<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870825-0122 </DOCNO><HL> International Corporate Report:Holmes a Court IncreasesJohn Fairfax Stake to 3.2%</HL><DD> 08/25/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)EARNINGS (ERN)PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN><TEXT>   The Australian financier Robert Holmes a Court has almost doubled, to 3.2%, his stake in the Australian publishing company JOHN FAIRFAX LTD. over the past two months, Fairfax's Australian Financial Review Daily reported.    In Australian trading yesterday, Fairfax's shares rose to 6.24 Australian dollars ($4.44) from 5.96 dollars Friday. In June, the company was trading at 4.50 dollars.    TNT Ltd., an Australia-based international transportation company, also has been building up a Fairfax stake and currently holds 3.4%, the Fairfax publication said. Neither Mr. Holmes a Court nor TNT have commented on their reasons for acquiring the stakes.    After Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., John Fairfax is the main publisher of newspapers in Australia. It also publishes magazines in Australia, Britain and the U.S.    Separately, Bell Resources Ltd., one of Mr. Holmes a Court's main investment vehicles, said after-tax operating profit rose 34% in the first half, to 100.3 million dollars ($71.5 million) from 74.7 million dollars a year earlier. After taking into account Bell's equity interest in associated companies and including extraordinary earnings, total profit jumped 74%, to 172.6 million dollars from 98.9 million dollars. Operating revenue rose 154%, to 2.33 billion dollars ($1.66 billion) from 919 million dollars. </TEXT></DOC>